com.google.android.agera

Class Result<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.android.agera.Result<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The output value type.

    public final class Result<T>
extends java.lang.Object
    An immutable object encapsulating the result of an attempt. An attempt is a call to Function.apply(TFrom), Merger.merge(TFirst, TSecond) or Supplier.get() that may fail. This class helps avoid throwing exceptions from those methods, by encapsulating either the output value of those calls, or the failure encountered. In this way, an attempt always produces a Result whether it has succeeded() or failed().

    This class can also be used to wrap a nullable value for situations where the value is indeed null, but null is not accepted. In this case a Result instance representing a failed attempt to obtain a non-null value can be used in place of the nullable value.

      • get

        public T get()
      throws FailedResultException
        Returns the output value of the successful attempt that produced this result.
        Throws:
        FailedResultException - If this is the result of a failed() attempt. The failure is available from Throwable.getCause(). This is an unchecked exception because it is easily avoidable by first checking whether the attempt has succeeded() or failed(), or by using other fluent style methods to achieve the same purpose.

      • ifSucceededAttemptMergeFrom

        public <U,V> Result<V> ifSucceededAttemptMergeFrom(Supplier<U> mergeValueSupplier,
                                                   Merger<? super T,? super U,Result<V>> attemptMerger)
        Returns the result of a follow-up attempt to merge the output value encapsulated in this result with the value from the given mergeValueSupplier using the attemptMerger, or if this is the result of a failed() attempt, returns the sameFailure().

        This method is agnostic of the value type of the mergeValueSupplier. If it is also fallible, the attemptMerger has the responsibility to interpret the result should the supplier fail. The merger may choose to, for example, return the sameFailure() if this happens.
